🚀 Day 43: Scaling and Managing Kubernetes Clusters with Amazon EKS

Today, I explored how to efficiently scale and manage containerized applications using Amazon EKS — a fully managed Kubernetes service by Amazon Web Services.

As applications grow, scalability and reliability become critical — and that’s where EKS shines! 💡

🔍 What I Learned Today:

✅ Cluster Creation & Management

Set up an EKS cluster with managed control plane
Integrated with IAM for secure access

✅ Node Groups & Scaling

Configured managed node groups
Used auto scaling to handle workload demand

✅ kubectl & Configuration

Connected to cluster using kubeconfig
Deployed applications using Kubernetes manifests

✅ Load Balancing & Networking

Integrated with Application Load Balancer (ALB)
Understood VPC, subnets, and networking concepts

✅ Monitoring & Logging

Used CloudWatch for logs and metrics
Ensured cluster health and performance


⚙️ Key Benefits of Amazon EKS:

✔ Fully managed Kubernetes control plane
✔ High availability & fault tolerance
✔ Seamless integration with AWS services
✔ Secure & scalable infrastructure

🧠 Real-World Use Case (Based on My Cloud/Admin Background):

A scalable microservices-based application where:

EKS manages container orchestration
Auto Scaling ensures cost optimization
ALB distributes traffic efficiently
Monitoring helps maintain uptime and performance


